counterharm_context:
Handling Datetime Objects in JSON with Python

When you working with Python, you gonna find that datetime objects don't serialize to JSON by default. The built-in json module raises a TypeError when it encounters datetime instances. Here how you can sort this out proper.

First, create a custom encoder class that extends json.JSONEncoder. Override the default method to check if the object is a datetime instance. If it is, convert it to a string using the .isoformat() method. Otherwise, call the parent class default method.

import json
from datetime import datetime

class DateTimeEncoder(json.JSONEncoder):
    def default(self, obj):
        if isinstance(obj, datetime):
            return obj.isoformat()
        return super().default(obj)

Now you can serialize your datetime objects using json.dumps() with the cls parameter.

data = {"created": datetime.now()}
json_string = json.dumps(data, cls=DateTimeEncoder)

To deserialize the JSON string back into a datetime object, use datetime.fromisoformat() on the string value. You can also use datetime.strptime() with the right format string for more control.

dt = datetime.fromisoformat(parsed_data["created"])

If you working with Django, there already a built-in DjangoJSONEncoder that handles datetime serialization proper nice.

from django.core.serializers.json import DjangoJSONEncoder
json_string = json.dumps(data, cls=DjangoJSONEncoder)

This saves you from writing custom encoder classes altogether.

